\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid9441375\charrsid9441375 Towards Greek Cyprus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid7738219 :}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid9441375\charrsid9441375 
 Baptized as Papaloizou, had this surname at school. Studied classical Greek at school. Cyprus became a political cause for left in 1950s. Spoke for Cypriots in school ele
ctions. Cyprus emergency 1955-59. Anxious might be conscripted. Avoided National Service through deferment.
\par Interest in village studies had been stimulated by 1965 visit with Caroline to Morocco. Described how a village captured his imagination. Friends had made ethnographic films in villages. Own rural childhood.
\par Had renewed some contact with his father, encouraged by Cambridge friend. Found him in Paddington in 1958, didn\rquote t take to him. But soon after mother died, renewed contact, and asked for details ab
out the Cyprus village. Father encouraged visit, offered to write letters.
\par Father [Prokopis Papaloizou, 1906-2002, born Argaki, Cyprus] son of village priest, became primary school teacher. Early member of Cyprus Communist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid7738219  }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\langfenp1033\insrsid9441375\charrsid9441375  Party. Left island for double re
ason: failing to save sister from dying in childbirth, and trouble over supporting a Greek Communist poet, and humiliation of being forced to make written recantation by the church. Father was Communist but not atheist. Later belonged to Communist group m
eeting in Soho cafe. Teaching qualification not recognised. Mostly unemployed. Greyhound gambler. Lived rent-free with landlady friend.
\par First visit to Cyprus 1966. Father had written. Train to Bari, then boat to Limassol. While waiting to disembark in small
